sketch-0.bodyMarkdown:
When related classes repeat the same attribute setup, that is a sign we can move the shared work into one base class.

```python
class Book:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title

class Movie:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title
```

Both classes store `title` the same way. A base class gives us one home for that repeated code.

sketch-1.bodyMarkdown:
After the base class exists, a subclass can start very small.

```python
class CatalogItem:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title

class Book(CatalogItem):
    pass
```

`Book` inherits the shared setup from `CatalogItem`, even before we add new book-specific details.

sketch-2.bodyMarkdown:
A subclass can use methods it did not write itself.

```python
class CatalogItem:
    def __init__(self, title):
        self.title = title

    def label(self):
        return self.title

class Book(CatalogItem):
    pass

book = Book("Dune")
print(book.label())
```

Because `Book` inherits from `CatalogItem`, `book.label()` already works.
